embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma (51%), benign spindle cell neoplasms, and infectious 
lesions (tuberculosis, fungal infections), were seen. Of the malignant tumors, 
those confined to the orbit achieved good treatment response and had an 
event-free follow-up while those with extraorbital spread had poor outcome. 
Pediatric orbital masses range from completely treatable infectious lesions, 
surgically resectable benign neoplasms to aggressive malignancies requiring 
chemotherapy and radiotherapy. Pathologists play a key role in distinguishing 
these on small biopsy material and expediating accurate treatment thus saving 
the vision or life of a patient.

